00:43.440 --> 00:44.880
video.

00:44.880 --> 00:49.720
Because this video doesn't cover what we guess about the universe, but what we know, and

00:49.720 --> 00:52.440
more importantly, how we know it.

00:52.440 --> 01:01.060
How do we know where the stars and galaxies came from and how old they are?

01:01.060 --> 01:04.960
The first person to take a stab at gauging the scale of the world around him was the

01:04.960 --> 01:08.340
Greek scientist Eratosthenes of Cyrene.

01:08.340 --> 01:13.000
He knew that on the longest day of the year, the sun was directly overhead at Syene in

01:13.000 --> 01:17.480
the south of Egypt, but cast a shadow in Alexandria to the north.

01:17.480 --> 01:22.260
By measuring the length of the shadow, he could work out the Earth's diameter.

01:22.260 --> 01:27.260
And while the Earth might be spherical, the dogma of a fixed Earth still held sway, backed

01:27.260 --> 01:29.820
by a powerful church.

01:29.820 --> 01:34.520
Problem was, this didn't fit the observable evidence, especially the observation that

01:34.520 --> 01:40.760
some wandering stars, or planets in Greek, had very erratic orbits around the Earth.

01:40.760 --> 01:44.980
When the telescope was invented, these planets turned out to be very different to the fixed

01:44.980 --> 01:46.140
stars.

01:46.140 --> 01:51.260
But it wasn't until Johannes Kepler calculated the exact orbits of the planets that a model

01:51.260 --> 01:54.740
of the solar system at last fit the observations.

01:54.740 --> 02:02.320
His law of planetary motion turned this into this.

02:02.320 --> 02:07.660
In the 18th century, a transit of Venus across the sun, timed at opposite ends of the Earth,

02:07.660 --> 02:12.540
made it possible to calculate the exact distance of the sun, and by extension the distances

02:12.540 --> 02:14.600
of all the known planets.

02:14.600 --> 02:16.980
But that still left the stars.

02:16.980 --> 02:21.080
The easiest way to measure their distance is a system called triangulation, which is

02:21.080 --> 02:23.940
used to measure distant objects on Earth.

02:23.940 --> 02:27.820
With stars, the baseline is the Earth's orbit around the sun.

02:27.820 --> 02:34.900
Take an angle measurement here, and six months later here, and just do the math.

02:34.900 --> 02:39.460
This principle was known in the 17th century, that their instruments simply weren't accurate

02:39.460 --> 02:42.380
enough to measure such a tiny angle.

02:42.380 --> 02:45.740
But in 1838 the technology had caught up.

02:45.740 --> 02:51.140
The Prussian astronomer Bessel found that the binary star 61 Cygni was an astounding

02:51.140 --> 02:53.260
60 trillion miles away.

02:53.260 --> 02:57.440
It was a distance so huge that it had to be measured in terms of the number of years it

02:57.440 --> 03:01.820
took light to cross it, 10.3 light years.

03:01.820 --> 03:05.740
Our universe just got bigger.

03:05.740 --> 03:10.500
Triangulation only works for stars up to 100 light years away, but it was a start.

03:10.500 --> 03:14.780
Knowing the distances of these stars, astronomers could work out the relationship between a

03:14.820 --> 03:19.900
star's distance and its brightness, because closer stars are generally brighter than distant

03:19.900 --> 03:21.340
ones.

03:21.340 --> 03:25.500
Using this calculation, they could now estimate the distance of the faintest stars they could

03:25.500 --> 03:26.500
see.

03:26.500 --> 03:30.380
It was only an estimate, but our universe got bigger again.

03:30.380 --> 03:35.940
We seemed to be on the edge of a huge wheel of stars in space.

03:35.940 --> 03:40.220
While the brightness of a star gives us an estimate of its distance, confirmation comes

03:40.220 --> 03:43.020
in another trick of triangulation.

03:43.020 --> 03:47.060
In 1987, a star was seen to explode inside our galaxy.

03:47.060 --> 03:51.740
The exploding star is called a supernova, and it's very bright.

03:51.740 --> 03:56.560
As it happened, this particular supernova was surrounded by a huge gas cloud far out

03:56.560 --> 03:57.900
into space.

03:57.900 --> 04:03.260
The light from the exploding supernova raced across the gap, and eight months later it

04:03.260 --> 04:05.460
hit the surrounding gas cloud.

04:05.460 --> 04:08.980
Cosmologists saw the reflective glow.

04:08.980 --> 04:13.220
We know the speed of light, so we know how far it can travel in eight months.

04:13.220 --> 04:17.520
And that means we know the distance between the supernova and the gas cloud.

04:17.520 --> 04:22.140
All cosmologists had to do is measure the angle between the two, as seen from Earth,

04:22.140 --> 04:25.020
and once again its simple triangulation.

04:25.020 --> 04:30.780
We can work out the distance of the supernova, 169,000 light years.

04:30.780 --> 04:37.660
That means we're looking at an event that happened 169,000 years ago.

04:37.660 --> 04:39.900
The universe was now huge.

04:39.900 --> 04:45.900
By simply observing and measuring, we'd calculated a scale in time and space that was far greater

04:45.900 --> 04:49.220
than Bronze Age people ever imagined.

04:49.220 --> 04:52.320
But one question still confounded scientists.

04:52.320 --> 04:54.980
What are all these stars made of?

04:54.980 --> 04:59.340
To understand the evidence, we have to understand the atom.

04:59.340 --> 05:03.260
